00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:26.119
balance and things like that for us. So it's a large kind of cross-section of different

00:08:26.119 --> 00:08:31.640
responsibilities, some interaction between them, but it's been a really interesting role.

00:08:34.039 --> 00:08:37.400
I have one more thing to add to that too, but I already saw a question about why was that

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:41.880
boss a great boss? And so I want to tackle that because he was a great boss. He actually now

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:48.520
works for Toyota. He hasn't been my boss in like 10 years, and we still keep in contact,

00:08:48.679 --> 00:08:52.919
still good friends. And why was the boss who hired me at Direct TV a great boss?

00:08:53.640 --> 00:09:01.080
Purely because he got me, he had a really great way of getting us excited about the impact that

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:06.760
we can make, right? At Direct TV, when we were helping with field, so we would do things where

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:11.880
we would launch new products, and then our team would be responsible for not truly A-B testing,

00:09:11.880 --> 00:09:15.479
but like measuring the effectiveness of the products and trying to compare them to similar

00:09:15.479 --> 00:09:22.679
products and things like that. And he did such a great job of connecting the work we were doing

00:09:23.239 --> 00:09:28.679
to the value that we were creating for clients and we were creating for the firm. And so it really

00:09:28.679 --> 00:09:32.280
made me excited to come to work every day. I think that was probably one of the first times

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:36.760
in my career that I was excited to come to work. And after I would go home, I would still be

00:09:36.760 --> 00:09:42.440
thinking about problems at work. So it was kind of different. And then the one last thing I'll

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:49.239
mention about Schwab is I also currently, I still work with the University of Denver,

00:09:49.880 --> 00:09:54.359
with my old department, which is now rebranded as the Business Information and Analytics Departments.

00:09:55.320 --> 00:10:02.200
I'm hoping I may have some students from DU on with us today, but we do regular capstone projects

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:07.960
with them. So that's really cool to be able to connect real world data to problems or projects

00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:14.760
at the undergrad and graduate level. And I also help run the data science at Schwab user group.

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:19.159
We actually have a meeting here in about an hour and a half. I don't know how I scheduled the data

00:10:19.159 --> 00:10:23.239
science hangout and the data science user group on the same day, but we've got a meeting in about

00:10:23.239 --> 00:10:28.840
an hour and a half where we're going to be talking about a Python app that some folks have built to

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:36.200
do NLP, interactive NLP analysis. So it's really cool, really exciting. So I think I'll pause there.

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:38.359
That's probably enough talking about myself. See if there's any questions.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:45.239
Oh, that's awesome. Big community day for you. One thing about yourself I forgot to ask you,

00:10:45.239 --> 00:10:49.400
what about something you like to do in your free time too? I always love getting to hear these.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:56.440
Oh yeah, that's a great question. So I think as Rachel knows, I'm based in Colorado.

00:10:57.799 --> 00:11:01.479
I should be a skier or a snowboarder. I'm actually a fifth generation native.

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:08.280
And my great, great grandfather came to Colorado specifically to compete in ski jump championships.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:14.119
And I have never skied or snowboarded in my life. And so I feel, I can already feel the

00:11:14.119 --> 00:11:17.400
disappointment from Rachel and probably from others that I've never skied or snowboarded.

00:11:18.039 --> 00:11:21.479
You're asking about what I like to do though. So that's not, that's kind of the opposite.

00:11:22.280 --> 00:11:28.119
I'm a big fan of just being outside. Anything, anything hiking, paddle boarding was been

00:11:28.119 --> 00:11:33.479
something I picked up recently. And then building too. I've been really into woodworking

00:11:33.479 --> 00:11:40.200
and 3D printing probably most recently during the pandemic. My two sons and I, we got a 3D

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:44.679
printer and built it ourselves and then are now printing things from the printer we built. So

00:11:44.679 --> 00:11:49.799
that's pretty awesome. I love it. Cool. Maybe one of these days we'll get you on a mountain.

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:57.960
I know we kind of covered a little bit of this in Russell's question about why that boss was

00:11:57.960 --> 00:12:05.080
a great boss. But I see Jared had a question as well. I know you said you, I'll read it, Jared.

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:10.679
Can you discuss any mentors or people that you have come across that helped shape your career

00:12:10.679 --> 00:12:16.760
journey? Maybe it was this boss, but also any specific stories of events that might have

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:24.840
changed your trajectory? Yeah, absolutely. I've been really fortunate that I've had a mentor at

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:30.760
probably each role that I've been at. And even early on, this is again, is going to date myself,

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:37.159
but one of the mentors I had when I worked for Mercer in actual consulting, this was fresh

00:12:37.159 --> 00:12:43.880
out of school. I was just kind of bright eyed and knew a lot of the, maybe the technical things

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:49.239
I needed to know, but not of the business side, the relationship building and networking and

00:12:49.960 --> 00:12:56.200
offering to help people when they didn't necessarily, I didn't necessarily get anything

00:12:56.200 --> 00:13:01.320
back from that side, just volunteering and things like that. And so I had a great mentor there,

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:09.080
who's also still a friend 15 years later. And he suggested, he gave me really tangible suggestions

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:13.400
of things to build my career. At that time, one of the basic things was like learning,

00:13:13.559 --> 00:13:18.200
what is it called? Mail merge in Word, between Word and Excel. That sounds like so outdated now,

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:24.280
but the idea that you could like, not really program something, but you could create something

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:30.840
that you can scale up to one iteration or 10 or a thousand or a hundred thousand, right?

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:35.559
It was really interesting. Also building some of my technical coding skills. We had a platform,

00:13:35.559 --> 00:13:41.479
like a proprietary platform that was SQL based. So I learned a lot of SQL-like

00:13:42.200 --> 00:13:47.080
terms there. And then even more recently at Schwab, we've had, I've had some great mentors

00:13:47.080 --> 00:13:52.359
who've talked to me about like thinking about personal brand and think about, when someone,

00:13:52.359 --> 00:13:58.280
when I'm in a room and I'm, or when people are in a room and I'm not there and they say things

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:01.559
about me, like, what are they talking? Is it positive? Is it negative? Do they even know who

00:14:01.559 --> 00:14:07.880
I am? That's probably the first battle. So trying to get that personal brand out there and being

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:14.280
kind of aware of what your reputation is at a firm.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:22.280
That's great. I mean, it's very clear you have a focus on relationships as well,

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:27.880
with both of these examples, saying you're still in touch with people 10 or 15 years later too.

00:14:30.039 --> 00:14:34.280
Veronica, I see you had a question a little bit earlier. Do you want to jump in here and ask that?

00:14:38.840 --> 00:14:47.719
I'm a walking desk. I wasn't walking. I was just curious how some of the approach or methods

00:14:47.719 --> 00:14:54.520
you, especially from the boss you learned, that you took to major success with your customers?

00:14:56.919 --> 00:15:00.840
Yeah, absolutely. I can probably talk about that most recently from Schwab because we've taken

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:07.719
quite a few, in the past two or three years, we've taken a lot of learnings from Gartner

00:15:07.719 --> 00:15:14.200
and from other folks in industry who do research about these things, because measuring data science

00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:23.080
projects or BI or analytics projects, anything really is tough, right? A lot of them, we have

00:15:23.080 --> 00:15:28.520
this idea maybe after the fact of what it might be worth, but it's hard to get that up front. So

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:34.280
about two or three years ago, we went through a pretty robust process at Schwab to try to

00:15:34.280 --> 00:15:41.799
understand what the expected value of a project could be. And so we got really

00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:51.799
down into the details and the weeds from this and thought about, is this satisfying a regulatory

00:15:51.799 --> 00:15:57.559
need? Is it satisfying a business need? Is it an efficiency play? Are we just making life easier

00:15:57.559 --> 00:16:02.919
for people? And how can we quantify those things, right? Efficiency, generally, I think was,

00:16:02.919 --> 00:16:07.719
from my experience, was one of the more easier ones, right? If I can save somebody 15 minutes a

00:16:07.719 --> 00:16:13.080
day by automating this process or creating this dashboard that they can go to, we can turn that

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:19.159
into dollars pretty easily. Where it gets tough is the research and development side of like,

00:16:20.119 --> 00:16:26.840
what would be the value of this model if we built it and it was accurate and could we use it to

00:16:26.840 --> 00:16:33.559
leverage that? So that's the side that's a little bit more, at least up front, it's tough to assess.

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:38.679
One thing that we've had a lot of success with was providing kind of ranges and estimates too.

00:16:38.679 --> 00:16:45.159
Like if this is fully successful, it might be X. And if it's partially successful, it might be Y.

00:16:45.159 --> 00:16:49.799
So it gives you kind of a threshold. And really, at the end of the day, I don't think the dollars

00:16:49.799 --> 00:16:57.239
or the values matter as much as they do for helping us prioritize, right? So if we have this

00:16:57.239 --> 00:17:02.200
set of expectations, we think about which of these projects is our actual top priority, and then we

00:17:02.200 --> 00:17:07.239
can stack rank them a little bit easier. So I don't know if that answers your question.

00:17:08.439 --> 00:17:11.479
No, this is helpful. Thank you so much. Absolutely.

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:17.719
I see Arsena's had a question for me to read. But the question was, what methods did you use

00:17:17.719 --> 00:17:23.560
to learn what you needed to in order to perform analytical work in such different domains

00:17:24.439 --> 00:17:27.640
as people analytics, then customer analytics, and now product?

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:34.839
Yeah, absolutely. I think, you know, my move to Schwab was probably the only time

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:44.040
in my career that I made a purposeful move for a domain, right? So up to that point in my career,

00:17:44.599 --> 00:17:51.640
six years ago, I had seen lots of different areas and ways to use analytics, to use data science.

00:17:52.599 --> 00:17:57.560
And the two that stuck out to me the most were definitely marketing analytics and biostats.

00:17:57.560 --> 00:18:03.880
That seemed like both of them, you needed to have, you know, you needed to be able to

00:18:04.119 --> 00:18:10.680
have like a PhD in biology, plus like a PhD in data science, if you wanted to go into biostats,

00:18:10.680 --> 00:18:15.400
or in marketing, you needed 20 years of marketing experience, plus 20 years of data science,

00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:19.479
you know, it was really tough to get into. And so that's, you know, one of the things I targeted.

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:27.479
Prior to that, I don't know that I was as purposeful. So when I was in Actuarial Sciences,

00:18:27.479 --> 00:18:33.160
I was learning the coding that I needed to know to support my clients. So, you know, for that part,

00:18:33.160 --> 00:18:39.959
it was mostly SQL, some BBA as well. In HR analytics, you know, again, SQL and some other

00:18:39.959 --> 00:18:47.079
tools at DirecTV, it was Oracle Business Intelligence, and it was, you know, SQL,

00:18:47.079 --> 00:18:51.719
that's when I started using R and Python as well to, you know, kind of expand those skill sets,

00:18:51.719 --> 00:19:00.040
SAS. So the approach that I started taking at Schwab is that I really want to get the widest

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:03.239
breadth of experience that I can, right? I think as data practitioners,

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:10.599
if we have the skill sets, we can apply them to any data problem. And I kind of use the analogy

00:19:10.599 --> 00:19:16.359
of like building a house, right? If you're hiring somebody to build your house, you don't care which

00:19:16.359 --> 00:19:20.280
tools they're going to use. You just care if they're going to do a good job, are they going

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:24.680
to meet your expectations, those types of things. And so the more experience they get building

00:19:24.680 --> 00:19:28.760
different types of things and approaching unusual situations, especially the ones where when you

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:33.640
start out, you have no idea what you're doing. You have no idea how to solve it. Those are

00:19:33.640 --> 00:19:39.400
probably the most fun ones. So, you know, just continuing to tackle new types of data and not

00:19:39.400 --> 00:19:44.119
necessarily coming in and being the expert. And that's kind of how I feel today with my new role

00:19:45.160 --> 00:19:49.560
supporting a new group within Schwab. I'm coming in and I know very little about the data behind

00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:52.760
it, but I'm learning every day, which is the best part of that role.

00:19:52.839 --> 00:19:56.520
I see everybody wants me to read the questions today. I don't know if everybody's

00:19:57.079 --> 00:20:00.920
coffee shops or what. I feel like that. Did I? I think I scared everybody off.

00:20:03.719 --> 00:20:10.439
But Jared asked the question, what is harder explaining ML, AI to decision holders or

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:12.920
getting buy in from stakeholders?

00:20:13.319 --> 00:20:18.839
That's a great question. If I can caveat the question to explaining ML and AI,

00:20:20.439 --> 00:20:30.520
maybe realistically, outside of the hype, I might say that. So we've seen a lot of those terms. And,

00:20:30.520 --> 00:20:36.439
you know, frequently when I hear some of the projects, the way that I would think about it is

00:20:37.319 --> 00:20:44.040
not, you know, ML or AI, I would think of it as automation or maybe regex, right? Like this can be

00:20:44.040 --> 00:20:48.760
solved through that. This can be, this is a report, you know, things like that. You know, we

